<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?><feed xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom" ><generator uri="https://jekyllrb.com/" version="3.7.3">Jekyll</generator><link href="http://localhost:4000/feed.xml" rel="self" type="application/atom+xml" /><link href="http://localhost:4000/" rel="alternate" type="text/html" /><updated>2018-03-10T15:37:05+01:00</updated><id>http://localhost:4000/</id><title type="html">himynameismarcel</title><subtitle>A bit of economics, data and programming.</subtitle><entry><title type="html">A Collapsible Tree with D3.js</title><link href="http://localhost:4000/Collapsible-Tree-With-D3js" rel="alternate" type="text/html" title="A Collapsible Tree with D3.js" /><published>2018-03-02T13:15:36+01:00</published><updated>2018-03-02T13:15:36+01:00</updated><id>http://localhost:4000/Collapsible-Tree-With-D3js</id><content type="html" xml:base="http://localhost:4000/Collapsible-Tree-With-D3js">&lt;p&gt;In this post I will try to describe as clearly as possible the generation of a tree-diagram using the javascript library D3.js.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The reason I stumbled over this in the first place is that when diving into Tableau we had stumbled over the possibility to create node-tree diagrams. In particular, Jeffrey Shaffer pioneered the generation of such node-tree diagrams in Tableau.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;div style=&quot;height: 800px; width: 1000;&quot; id=&quot;example&quot;&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;style&gt;

.node {
  cursor: pointer;
}

.node circle {
  fill: #fff;
  stroke: steelblue;
  stroke-width: 1.5px;
}

.node text {
  font: 10px sans-serif;
}

.link {
  fill: none;
  stroke: #ccc;
  stroke-width: 1.5px;
}

&lt;/style&gt;

&lt;script src=&quot;https://cdnjs.cloudflare.com/ajax/libs/d3/3.5.6/d3.min.js&quot;&gt;&lt;/script&gt;

